<h1>Step 3 ŌĆö Get PDFs in a way that wonŌĆÖt limit you (legal + reproducible)</h1>
<h2>3A) Fast path for Open Access PDFs (automation-friendly)</h2>
<p>Add one tool to your toolkit: <strong>Unpaywall</strong> (free API; no key). It often returns a direct OA PDF URL for a DOI.</p>
<p><strong>What you do:</strong> for each DOI in the worklist, call Unpaywall ŌåÆ if it returns <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">best_oa_location.url_for_pdf</code>, download it into <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">forlitrev_pdfs\</code>, update <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">primary_file</code>.</p>
<p>This is the single most effective ŌĆ£not limitedŌĆØ improvement because it turns ŌĆ£hunt papers manuallyŌĆØ into ŌĆ£resolve OA link ŌåÆ downloadŌĆØ.</p>
<p>(You already use OpenAlex; OpenAlex also provides OA locations sometimes, but Unpaywall is purpose-built for OA PDF resolution.)</p>
<h2>3B) If not OA: institutional access / ILL / author copy (still reproducible)</h2>
<p>For paywalled DOIs, the clean options are:</p>
<ul>
<li>University/library ŌĆ£Find it @ ŌĆ”ŌĆØ via DOI</li>
<li>Interlibrary loan</li>
<li>Author accepted manuscript via email / institutional repository</li>
</ul>
<p>Pipeline-wise, you can still keep the record in your mapping results, but mark <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">fulltext_available=0</code> if you canŌĆÖt obtain the PDF.</p>
<hr>
<h1>Step 4 ŌĆö Eliminate DOCX as a blocker (convert to PDF or replace with publisher PDF)</h1>
<h3>Best: replace DOCX with official publisher PDF</h3>
<p>If the DOI exists, prefer the official PDF.</p>
