<h2>3) What to do for genuinely hard-to-get (paywalled / obscure) tropical resources</h2>
<p>Some tropical-context papers <em>will</em> be legitimately difficult (regional journals, older Taylor &amp; Francis, some IEEE/IOP items depending on access). For those, the academically clean options are:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Institutional library access by DOI</strong> (often works even when Google doesnŌĆÖt).</li>
<li><strong>Interlibrary loan (ILL)</strong> ŌĆö surprisingly effective for older/obscure items.</li>
<li><strong>Author request</strong> (email corresponding author; ask for ŌĆ£author accepted manuscriptŌĆØ if the VoR is paywalled).</li>
<li><strong>Institutional repositories</strong> (many authors deposit accepted manuscripts).</li>
<li><strong>Adjust your reviewŌĆÖs extraction tier</strong>:<!-- -->
<ul>
<li>keep the record in the <em>mapping</em> dataset (RQ1/RQ2) if you have metadata/abstract,</li>
<li>but mark <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">fulltext_available=0</code> so itŌĆÖs excluded from ŌĆ£validation rigor / preprocessing transparencyŌĆØ extraction (RQ3ŌĆōRQ6).<br>
<!-- -->That is a normal, defensible scoping-review practiceŌĆöjust report it in limitations.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<p>(Do <strong>not</strong> use piracy sources; it creates ethical and reproducibility problems for the manuscript.)</p>
