6913 16.1437 14.3892 16.561 14.646L21.8789 17.9174Z" stroke="currentColor"></path></svg><div class="text-interactive-normal text-sm">No Sources</div></div></div><div class="prose prose-sm prose-pre:bg-transparent prose-pre:p-0 text-wrap break-words"><p>That error is coming from <strong>the GitHub Gist HTTP upload path</strong> (what <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">gh gist create</code> uses). With <strong>115 files</strong> in one request, GitHub (or something in-between your machine and GitHubŌĆöproxy/firewall) is terminating the connection:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">wsarecv: An existing connection was forcibly closed by the remote host</code></p>
</blockquote>
<p>So nothing is wrong with your staging. ItŌĆÖs the <em>upload method</em>.</p>
<p>You have two fixes that work on Windows PowerShell with your exact setup. The best one (most reliable, least fiddly) is to treat the gist as a <strong>git remote</strong> and <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">git push</code> the files. That avoids the ŌĆ£multi-file API POSTŌĆØ that keeps failing.</p>
<hr>
<h1>Fix (Recommended): Create a secret gist, then push your scripts to it via <strong>git</strong></h1>
<p>This is custom-fit to your reality because:</p>
<ul>
<li>you already have git set up</li>
<li>you already have a clean staged folder: <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">.\_gist_share\scripts\</code></li>
<li>you already have a small snapshot zip (347 KB) if we want to include it too</li>
<li>pushing via git handles lots of files cleanly and allows binaries (zip) too</li>
</ul>
