<hr>
<h1>C. What to add so the work is ŌĆ£not limitedŌĆØ</h1>
<p>Think in three tiers: <strong>required</strong>, <strong>strongly recommended</strong>, <strong>optional but removes edge-case limits</strong>.</p>
<h2>C1) Required additions (for robust PDF extraction)</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>OCRmyPDF + Tesseract + Ghostscript</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Solves scanned PDFs / image-only papers (a common blocker).</li>
<li>OCRmyPDF is designed specifically to add an OCR text layer to PDFs. <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://pypi.org/project/ocrmypdf/" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">2</span></span></a></span></li>
</ul>
<ol start="2">
<li><strong>A reproducible GROBID runtime</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Either Dockerized GROBID or a pinned local install.</li>
<li>Batch <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">processFullText</code> is the workhorse for TEI extraction. <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://grobid.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Grobid-batch/" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">3</span></span></a></span></li>
</ul>
<h2>C2) Strongly recommended (to keep things scalable + auditable)</h2>
<ol start="3">
<li><strong>A local ŌĆ£evidence packŌĆØ store in DuckDB or SQLite</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Your CSV registries are great, but once you start storing chunks + evidence spans, a small DB makes querying/auditing far easier (e.g., ŌĆ£show all papers with <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">validation_type=random</code> AND <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">N_matchups&lt;50</code> AND <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">tropical=1</code>ŌĆØ).</li>
</ul>
<ol start="4">
<li><strong>Vector store choice + a lexical fallback</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Keep <strong>Chroma or FAISS</strong> for semantic retrieval. <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.trychroma.com/" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">4</span></span></a></span></li>
<li>Add a simple lexical search fallback (even just SQLite FTS or ripgrep over Markdown) for exact phrases like ŌĆ£atmospheric correctionŌĆØ, ŌĆ£ACOLITEŌĆØ, ŌĆ£Sen2CorŌĆØ, ŌĆ£adjacency effectŌĆØ, etc. (semantic search alone sometimes misses exact-method strings).</li>
</ul>
<ol start="5">
<li><strong>A ŌĆ£paper_id Ōåö pdf Ōåö teiŌĆØ naming convention</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>The #1 operational failure in evidence-pack projects is broken mapping. Make it deterministic:<!-- -->
<ul>
<li>file name = sanitized DOI when available</li>
<li>else = your internal <code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">paper_id</code></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2>C3) Optional (these remove remaining ŌĆ£limitationsŌĆØ)</h2>
<ol start="6">
<li><strong>Table extraction tools (only if you truly need numeric tables)</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>If you want to pull matchup counts/metrics from tables reliably:<!-- -->
<ul>
<li><code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">camelot</code> (good for lattice-style tables)</li>
<li><code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">tabula-py</code> (often good, but depends on Java)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Many reviews donŌĆÖt need this, because the key items (validation type, AC method, matchup window) are typically in Methods text, not only tables.</li>
</ul>
<ol start="7">
<li><strong>A reference manager bridge</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>If your manuscript will be in Word/LaTeX, consider managing BibTeX/CSL properly:<!-- -->
<ul>
<li>Zotero (+ Better BibTeX) or JabRef</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>This doesnŌĆÖt extract from PDFs per se, but it prevents citation chaos later.</li>
</ul>
<ol start="8">
<li><strong>Workflow orchestration (Snakemake or Make)</strong></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Not essential, but it turns your pipeline into one command:<!-- -->
<ul>
<li><code class="rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-surface-tertiary font-mono text-[0.9em] text-text-primary font-medium" node="[object Object]">snakemake -j 8 build_evidence_pack</code></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Big benefit: you can re-run only what changed (e.g., ŌĆ£only OCR new PDFsŌĆØ, ŌĆ£only GROBID missing TEIŌĆØ).</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1>D. The ŌĆ£no limitationsŌĆØ target state (what youŌĆÖre aiming for)</h1>
<p>If you implement the above, the only remaining limitations will be <em>non-technical</em> (e.g., paywalled PDFs you donŌĆÖt possess, or papers with extremely poor scan quality).</p>
<p>Your end state should look like:</p>
<ul>
