<h1>6) What to emphasize in the ŌĆ£DiagnosisŌĆØ results (so the critique lands)</h1>
<p>These are the <em>highest-yield critique levers</em> in RSŌĆōML inland water papers:</p>
<h3>6.1 Validation leakage: why random splits can be misleading</h3>
<p>Spatial autocorrelation means nearby samples are similar; random train/test splits often leak spatial structure and inflate performance. This is a known issue in spatial prediction, and spatially-aware CV/blocking is widely recommended. <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/311523792_Cross-validation_strategies_for_data_with_temporal_spatial_hierarchical_or_phylogenetic_structure" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">10</span></span></a></span></p>
<h3>6.2 Preprocessing opacity: why it matters more than most ML papers admit</h3>
<p>For inland waters, performance is often dominated by:</p>
<ul>
<li>atmospheric correction choice/settings, <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.mdpi.com/2072-4292/9/4/322" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">15</span></span></a></span></li>
<li>adjacency effect (especially small lakes), <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.mdpi.com/2072-4292/14/8/1829" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">14</span></span></a></span></li>
<li>glint/edge masking and cloud masking (often underreported but decisive for matchups). <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.usgs.gov/data/sentinel-2-acolite-dsf-aquatic-reflectance-conterminous-united-states" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">6</span></span></a></span></li>
</ul>
<p>So your review can credibly argue: <strong>ŌĆ£Many papers are not reproducible in principle, because the reflectance they modeled cannot be reconstructed.ŌĆØ</strong></p>
<h3>6.3 Optically complex (ŌĆ£Case 2ŌĆØ) waters: the mechanism behind fragility</h3>
<p>In Case 2 waters, CDOM and sediments can vary independently of chlorophyll; that breaks simple band-ratio assumptions and increases the need for careful modeling + validation. <span class="inline-flex p-0.5" data-state="closed"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0278434302002224" class="focus-visible:ring-ring inline-flex rounded-sm no-underline focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2"><span class="bg-surface-raised inline-flex h-4 w-4 items-center justify-center rounded-sm p-0.5 cursor-pointer"><span class="text-center font-['Inter'] text-[10px] font-normal leading-3 text-interactive-link">16</span></span></a></span></p>
